caption: Remains as one of most Favourite restaurants in Brookline. I was craving for lotus root and wantan on Sunday evening and Sichuan Gourmet delivered in an amazing way. We ordered the spicy wantan in Szechuan chili sauce and the mixed vegetables savory pot. The pick up order on the phone was incredibly easy and my food was prepared in record time. And when I picked up my food, the packing was very well thought of where the savory pot was in a foil container and a cardboard "coaster" to keep it from collapsing. Another thing I loved was the fact that there was not anything extra like chopsticks etc because why would you give me disposable wear when I don't need it. This was very eco-conscious and thoughtful! Thank you! Of course when we got home and had our food, everything was delicious and hit the spot on my cravings. It made me feel like I was home (Malaysia) again (especially with the wantan). Thank you for remaining awesome on amazing food, excellent service, and thoughtful packaging of my take out.

My husband (37) and I (28), both foreign citizens, tried to wine and dine here last night. We were seated in the restaurant with no one asking for our IDs. After deciding on the menu, we tried to order and were asked to produce an ID. The waiter said they'd only take original passports as ID (I offered to show him a scan and he refused). We were not aware of Massachusetts strict laws regarding acceptable IDs for alcohol sales but were not informed upon entrance. The staff was rude and did not try to accommodate us and convince us to stay for the food menu when we said we might go somewhere else. After we headed out, all other restaurants in the surroundings were closed so we had to go back home hungry. I wonder how much this was about  abiding by state laws and how much this was about discriminatory practices...

I’ve been coming to this place for years and it is always delicious and consistently high quality with great flavor and spice. The first couple of times I went we had a fish stew that was unlike anything else I had until I went to Nanjing, Shanghai, and Beijing. Some people might have issues with fish bones so that dish isn’t for everyone but if you order anything from their speciality menu you will not be disappointed.  My favorites are the bamboo shoots, green beans, and beef with hot peppers (careful- sometimes depending on the season the peppers can be very very spicy. I like it regardless of spice but it’s not for the weak of tongue).

First of all-- the food was delicious! This is not a slight on the food. However, our experience was one of the worst I've had with any restaurant. My friend and I were studying, but we both hadn't eaten that day. She called in our order, a PuPu for two, dumplings and a ginger ale. We waited 20 minutes, then went to pick it up. As we arrived, a woman was picking up her order and I jokingly said to my friend "I hope that's not ours." After she left we told the man behind the counter we called in our order half an hour ago. He suddenly chases the woman out the door, down the street, and brings her back inside where upon she says "my secretary called and added a pupu for two and dumplings half an hour ago, can I go now? This is my food." So he tells us there has been a mistake and we would have to wait for our food to be made again which would take some time. I pipe up that I have another meeting coming up in half an hour, is there any way he could reduce the price or add something else (we're about to eat our hands off at this point) for the inconvenience? I guess this is where the confusion happened. To our understanding, he was going to add green beans and rangoons to the order as a polite gesture to us for having waited patiently. When we got back to the apartment though, all we had was fried rice, rangoons and green beans (no soda) and we had still been charged over $30.00 before a tip. This wasn't right either, so we called in and asked to speak with him. I simply said, "I'm sorry, but I don't think we got what we ordered." Finally we figured out that because I said I was in a rush, he decided to change our order to make it come out faster. I said, "I'm sorry but that wasn't how we understood it and we're not happy paying almost $40 for this food as struggling college students." That's when he started berating me and yelling about me trying to get free food calling me "lady" and interrupting me every other word. "You want PuPu platter? Okay, you bring me green beans and rangoons and I'll give you pupu platter." Which I would have done, if I had the time and we hadn't already started eating. We were so hungry at this point. But even if I had done that, I wouldn't have been happy because my order hadn't been made when I called it in, I had waited for food I didn't order, charged for the food I DID order and then yelled at by staff over the phone, who I had to convince for over 10 minutes that re-making what we had ordered in the first place was the right thing to do. Plus, it's freezing outside and not enjoyable to make the 20 minute round trip walk for a mistake I didn't make. All in all not good customer service and I won't be back. It's a shame because the food we did receive was delicious, and I would love to frequent this place. I'm a waitress and my boss always encourages us to throw in free dessert, drinks or a coupon for next time for customers that have been inconvenienced-- and he doesn't wait for them to ask for it. It's just good business.

Great Sichuan restaurant, even when measured against Sichuan options in Chinatown. Doesn’t look like much on the inside, but the dining room is huge. It features a full bar and many large, round tables suited for groups. Occasionally, tour buses full of Chinese tourists pull up to this spot. This place is also popular with many Asian students as well as families.  Some highlights are the scallion pancake with beef, Sichuan dumplings with chili oil, Mandarin chicken, shredded beef with longhorn pepper, and the cumin lamb. Even though it might be sacrilege, this place does also have really killer crab rangoons.  Service is usually very responsive and quick, even for takeout. While not the cheapest in the area, the quality is good and consistent.

It tasted preserved and was dry.  The scallion pancakes were also weird, really fried.  This place is not one for atmosphere or service either.  I felt like I was sitting in a dirty dark old kitchen that badly needs a renovation.  But decent food and great location makes up for it.
